Mrs. Jack Naura) Banks. $40
w. Williams, Tucson, was named
as the Outstanding Woman Of the
Year for community service by
the Arizona Daily Star.


Mrs. Banks was one of eight
women to be cited for their con-
tributions in public service, bus
mess, philanthropy, the arts, and
education.


A native of Tucson, Mrs. Banks
received all of her education in
Tucson. She holds a bacherlor' s
degree from the University Of
Arizona and has done graduate
study at the University Of South
ern California.


She is the president of the
Tucson YWCA. being the first of
her race to be elected to this
post in the western region. She
has been a WV member since
1895.


Mrs. Banks has served on the
WV board since 1859 and was the
first vice president for two years.
In 1855 she was a delegate to the
YWCA convention in New York
and was chairman of the western
region YWCA.


A teacher in the elementary
public schools for 81 years. Mrs.
Banks has inspired many young
Students.


Mrs. Banks was also chosen
as the Tucson NAACP Woman of
the Year. She has served as pres
ident of the organization and this
year she Is chairman of the Com
munity Relations Committee.


She Is an organizer of the Eta
Epsilon Omega chapter of Alpha
Kappa Alpha Sorority and a past
president. She is presently pub
licity chairman of the chapter.
She also serves on the nominal
ing committee of the western
region and will attend the AKA
national meeting in Chicago in
March.


This year Mrs. Banks served
on the Tucson Advisory Commit
tee for Minority Employment
Problems, Arizona State EN-
ployment Service.


She is the wife of Jack Banks,
owner Of Jacks Drive Inns and
she serves as the personnel man
ager.

champion Sonny Liston will rent
a house on Miami Beach while
training for his Feb. Is fight
here with Cassius Clay. 1t was
reported.


Liston originally rented a
house in Miami 8 southwest Sec

The Phoenix Union High School
Board has passed regulations
in attendance coming to permit
students to cross zone boundaries
to attend the school of their
choice.


East, Hayden. North and Phoe-
nix Union will be open next fall
to students from all neighbor-
hoods, which in effect, ends any
segregation of Phoenix high
schools because of residence.


In the past, the only school
in the nine-school union district
open to students from all parts
of the city was Phoenix Union
High School.


The board action will bring few
athletic ramifications since the
new regulations state that a STU
dent attending outside his resi-
dence zone can't take part in
athletics for the first two Sc
mesterS.


In other action. the board
awarded the Arnold Construction
Co. of Phoenix the contract for
additions and remodeling at South
Mountain High on a bid of
$544, 1000.


If the work Is completed by
September, as scheduled. the
school will end double sessions.
